## 2. Why Blob Storage Uses Containers

### The Two-Level Hierarchy

Azure enforces a strict two-level hierarchy inside every storage account:

```
Storage Account
└── Container (e.g., user-uploads)
    └── Blob (e.g., avatar.jpg)
```

Think of a storage account as a **warehouse** and containers as the **rooms** inside it.

### Reasons for Containers

#### Access Control (RBAC & SAS)
Permissions can be assigned at the container level rather than on every individual blob:
- `private` — No anonymous access
- `blob` — Public read for blobs, private for container listing
- `container` — Full public read including listing

```
Container: profile-pictures   → Public read (anyone can view images)
Container: financial-reports  → Private (only authenticated users)
Container: temp-uploads       → SAS token access (time-limited)
```

#### Lifecycle Management
Lifecycle policies are applied at the container level:
```json
{
  "rules": [{
    "name": "move-old-blobs-to-cool",
    "filters": { "blobTypes": ["blockBlob"], "prefixMatch": ["user-uploads/"] },
    "actions": { "baseBlob": { "tierToCool": { "daysAfterModificationGreaterThan": 30 } } }
  }]
}
```

#### Namespace Isolation
Two blobs with the same name can coexist in different containers:
```
mycompanystorage / container-A / photo.jpg   ✅ Valid
mycompanystorage / container-B / photo.jpg   ✅ Valid (different container)
```

#### Scalability & Partitioning
Azure uses the container name as part of the **partition key** for load distribution. Separate containers = separate partitions = independent scaling.

#### Metadata & Tagging
Each container holds its own metadata dictionary:
```
Container: user-uploads
Metadata:
  department  = engineering
  environment = production
  owner       = platform-team
```

### Full Path Example

```
https://mycompanystorage.blob.core.windows.net/user-uploads/avatar.jpg
│                         │                    │             │
Account endpoint          │                    Container     Blob name
                          Service type
```

