## 4. Data Replication Across Availability Zones

### Replication Options

Azure offers four main replication strategies:

| Type | Copies | Protection | Use Case |
|---|---|---|---|
| **LRS** (Locally Redundant) | 3 copies in 1 datacenter | Hardware failure | Dev/test, low cost |
| **ZRS** (Zone Redundant) | 3 copies across 3 zones | Zone failure | Production workloads |
| **GRS** (Geo Redundant) | LRS + async copy to secondary region | Region failure | Business-critical data |
| **GZRS** (Geo-Zone Redundant) | ZRS + async copy to secondary region | Zone + region failure | Mission-critical data |

### Zone-Redundant Storage (ZRS) — Deep Dive

ZRS is the recommended baseline for production. It replicates your data **synchronously** across three availability zones within the same Azure region.

#### Write flow with ZRS

```
Your App: PUT avatar.jpg
        │
        ▼
Azure FE Layer accepts the request
        │
        ├──────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────┐
        │                          │                          │
        ▼                          ▼                          ▼
  Zone 1 Storage            Zone 2 Storage            Zone 3 Storage
  Cluster                   Cluster                   Cluster
  (Independent power,       (Independent power,       (Independent power,
   cooling, networking)      cooling, networking)      cooling, networking)
        │                          │                          │
  Replica 1 ✅              Replica 2 ✅              Replica 3 ✅
        │                          │                          │
        └──────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────┘
                                   │
                                   ▼
              201 Created returned to your app
         (only after ALL 3 zones confirm the write)
```

#### Within each zone

Each zone's storage cluster also has 3 internal replicas (across 3 storage nodes within the zone):

```
Zone 1 Storage Cluster
├── Node A (primary)
├── Node B (replica)
└── Node C (replica)
```

Total copy count with ZRS: **3 zones × 3 intra-zone nodes = 9 copies** of every blob.

#### Failure scenarios

| Failure | LRS | ZRS | GRS | GZRS |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Single disk failure | ✅ Survives | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |
| Server (node) failure | ✅ Survives | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |
| Datacenter (zone) failure | ❌ Data loss | ✅ Survives | ❌ | ✅ |
| Region-wide disaster | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ Survives (RPO ~15 min) | ✅ |

### GRS — Geo-Redundant Storage

With GRS, data is also asynchronously copied to a secondary region (typically 500+ miles away):

```
Primary Region (East US)          Secondary Region (West US)
┌──────────────────────┐          ┌──────────────────────────┐
│  LRS: 3 local copies │ ──────▶  │  LRS: 3 copies (async)   │
│  (synchronous)       │          │  Read-only unless failover│
└──────────────────────┘          └──────────────────────────┘
```

> **Note**: The secondary region is read-only by default. During a region failover, it becomes the primary. RPO (Recovery Point Objective) is typically under 15 minutes.

