## 5. Managing Mixed Content in a Single Container

### The core principle

At the infrastructure level, Azure treats **all blobs identically** — whether a JPEG, PDF, DOCX, or MP4. They are all byte streams. The file type is stored as metadata (`Content-Type`) and is only used when serving the file back to a client.

### How mixed content is stored

#### Container view (logical)

```
Container: user-uploads
├── avatar.jpg      (image/jpeg,      2.4 MB,  tier: Hot)
├── report.pdf      (application/pdf, 8.1 MB,  tier: Cool)
├── banner.png      (image/png,       512 KB,  tier: Hot)
└── notes.docx      (application/msword, 340 KB, tier: Cool)
```

#### Metadata layer (per-blob records, sorted by name)

```
Partition Key                          │ Metadata
───────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────
mycompanystorage/user-uploads/avatar   │ type=image/jpeg, size=2.4MB, Hot
mycompanystorage/user-uploads/banner   │ type=image/png,  size=512KB, Hot
mycompanystorage/user-uploads/notes    │ type=docx,       size=340KB, Cool
mycompanystorage/user-uploads/report   │ type=application/pdf, 8.1MB, Cool
```

Keys are sorted alphabetically — enabling fast prefix searches like `list all blobs starting with "report"`.

#### Extent store (physical bytes, interleaved)

```
Storage Node 1:
  ├── avatar.jpg  → Extent-A01 (bytes 0–1MB)
  ├── report.pdf  → Extent-B02 (bytes 2–4MB)
  └── banner.png  → Extent-C01 (entire file, small)

Storage Node 2:
  ├── avatar.jpg  → Extent-A02 (bytes 1–2.4MB)
  ├── report.pdf  → Extent-B01 (bytes 0–2MB)
  └── notes.docx  → Extent-D01 (entire file, packed with other small blobs)

Storage Node 3:
  ├── report.pdf  → Extent-B03 (bytes 4–8.1MB)
  ├── avatar.jpg  → Extent-A01 replica
  └── banner.png  → Extent-C01 replica
```

> Chunks from different file types are freely interleaved across nodes — the storage system doesn't group by file type.

### Access tier management per blob

Different tiers can coexist in the same container:

| Blob | Tier | Storage Medium | Retrieval Speed | Cost |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `avatar.jpg` | Hot | SSD / fast HDD | Immediate | Higher |
| `banner.png` | Hot | SSD / fast HDD | Immediate | Higher |
| `report.pdf` | Cool | Slower HDD | Immediate | Lower |
| `notes.docx` | Cool | Slower HDD | Immediate | Lower |
| `archive.zip` | Archive | Offline tape/disk | Hours (rehydration) | Lowest |

> Tier is stored in the metadata record per blob and can be changed at any time without moving the physical data to a different container.

### Virtual directories (prefix-based "folders")

Blob Storage has no real folders. However, you can simulate a folder structure using `/` in blob names:

```
user-uploads/
├── images/avatar.jpg       → blob name: "images/avatar.jpg"
├── images/banner.png       → blob name: "images/banner.png"
├── documents/report.pdf    → blob name: "documents/report.pdf"
└── documents/notes.docx    → blob name: "documents/notes.docx"
```

Azure's list API supports the `delimiter=/` parameter to return results as if they were in folders, even though the storage infrastructure sees these as flat keys.

